@{
    RootModule        = 'DriverAutomationTool.psm1'
    ModuleVersion     = '2.1.4'
    GUID              = 'a3f7b2c1-4d5e-6f78-9a0b-1c2d3e4f5678'
    Author            = 'Driver Automation Tool Contributors'
    Description       = 'Automates downloading, packaging, and distributing Dell and Lenovo drivers and BIOS updates for SCCM/ConfigMgr environments. 1.12.0 adds hardware-aware DriverUpdates installs: the Dell catalog''s per-driver PCI hardware IDs (VEN/DEV) are captured into manifest.json, and the apply script enumerates the device''s present PCI devices and skips any DUP whose target hardware is absent (conservative - DUPs that declare no hardware still run). This stops e.g. a Qualcomm NIC DUP from running on an Intel-NIC SKU and reduces the unneeded DUPs that get AV-quarantined. Adds a virtual-machine guard so AVD/VDI/Hyper-V/VMware hosts skip driver and BIOS installs entirely (apply-time guard plus a Model-not-Virtual requirement rule on new apps). Non-applicable DUPs whose .EXE was AV-quarantined no longer fail the deployment. 1.12.1 fixes the recurring "Could not set custom return codes ... Unable to find type [...ErrorClass]" failure: the SDK types (SccmSerializer/ErrorClass/CustomError) are now resolved by reflection off the loaded ConfigMgr assembly instead of PowerShell''s [typename] resolver, which never saw them on some console builds. This also restores the 1.11.5 deployment-type idempotency pre-check (it shared the same broken type reference and was silently falling back to "always update", re-introducing CI-revision churn), so vendor exit codes (Dell DUP 2/3/4/5/6, Lenovo 256) map correctly and apps stop churning revisions. 1.12.2 fixes the CMTrace log timestamp: the timezone bias was written as a hardcoded "+" followed by the raw UTC offset, so machines west of UTC logged "...+-300", which CMTrace couldn''t parse and showed a wrong/blank date-time on every line. Both loggers (Write-DATLog and the client apply script) now emit a correctly-signed bias. 1.12.3 fixes custom return codes still failing on 1.12.2 with "is loaded but does not expose expected type(s): ErrorClass, CustomError": those types live in a different SDK assembly than SccmSerializer on some console builds, and the 1.12.1/1.12.2 resolver only inspected a single DLL. The resolver now searches every loaded assembly per type and, if any are still missing, loads the whole ApplicationManagement* DLL family from the console bin directory before giving up. This also clears the companion "DT idempotency pre-check failed" line (same resolver), so no-op deployment-type updates stop bumping CI revisions. 1.12.4 finally fixes custom return codes on console builds where ErrorClass/CustomError cannot be located by name at all (1.12.3 force-loaded all ApplicationManagement* DLLs and still failed): the CustomError and ErrorClass types are now read directly off a live default return-code object on the deployment type (every script DT ships with default codes), so no by-name type lookup is needed. The serializer-only resolver no longer requires those two types, which also clears the "DT idempotency pre-check failed" line on these builds. 1.12.5 fixes the follow-on "Deployment type Installer has no CustomReturnCodes collection to update" error: a freshly-created script DT comes back with a null CustomReturnCodes (Add-CMScriptDeploymentType does not seed default codes), so there was nothing to sample. The CustomError and ErrorClass types are now read from the Installer''s CustomReturnCodes property-type metadata (always present, no live element or by-name lookup needed), and the collection is instantiated when null. 1.12.6 stops DriverUpdates Applications from forcing a restart after every run: the deployment type''s post-install behavior changes from ForceReboot to BasedOnExitCode for all modes, so a device only restarts when the install script returns 3010 (a Dell DUP/Flash64W 2/6, Lenovo SRSETUP 256, or pnputil 3010/259 that actually signaled reboot-required). A run where every DUP was skipped (hardware not present / already current) now exits 0 and does NOT reboot - fixing the "Success - no reboot required" run that still popped the restart countdown. With the deployment''s default RebootOutsideServiceWindow=$false, the genuine soft reboot is deferred to the collection''s maintenance window; re-syncing flips existing DriverUpdates apps to BasedOnExitCode in place. Also fixes the DATApply.log date/time in CMTrace: the trap and startup-marker lines were written as bare "[HH:mm:ss] ..." text in an otherwise CMTrace-formatted file, so CMTrace showed a wrong/blank date-time on those lines. All lines now share one CMTrace <![LOG[...]]> formatter, and timestamps render with InvariantCulture so a non-US client locale can''t corrupt the time separator. 1.13.0 adds an optional "Create / ensure maintenance window on collection" section to the Deploy Applications tab (and EnsureMaintenanceWindow / MWStart / MWDurationMinutes / MWRecurrence / MWDayOfWeek / MWName parameters on Invoke-DATDeployApplications). When enabled, a DAT-named maintenance window with a configurable start, duration, and None/Daily/Weekly recurrence is created or updated on the target collection before the apps are deployed, so a reboot the install script signals (exit 3010) is deferred to that window instead of firing right after install. The window is idempotent by name (updated in place if present, never duplicated, admin-created windows left untouched) and general (ApplyTo=Any), which also governs software updates and task sequences on the collection - the deploy confirmation warns before applying it to broad collections. 1.14.0 adds a standalone Scripts\Deploy-DATApplications.ps1 wrapper so the same bulk deployment (and the optional maintenance-window creation) can be driven from the command line, a scheduled task, or a runbook without the GUI. It forwards all Invoke-DATDeployApplications parameters - including EnsureMaintenanceWindow / MWStart / MWDurationMinutes / MWRecurrence / MWDayOfWeek / MWName - and returns an exit code for automation (0 = all deployments and the window succeeded, 1 = a deployment or the window failed, 2 = a fatal error). 1.15.0 stops an inapplicable graphics DUP from failing a DriverUpdates deployment. Dell ships every GPU option''s driver for a model and many graphics DUPs carry no PCIInfo, so on (for example) an AMD box the NVIDIA driver still ran and reported "no compatible hardware" as a generic exit 1 - failing the whole Application even though every driver the device needed had installed. The apply script now detects the GPU brands actually present (NVIDIA/AMD from display adapters and raw PCI, Intel from display adapters) and skips a graphics DUP for a brand that is not installed; if such a DUP still runs and errors, it is counted as not-applicable instead of a failure - unless that brand''s GPU IS present, in which case it is still surfaced as a real failure. The DriverUpdates summary gains a "skipped (GPU brand absent)" count. Re-sync to restage the updated apply script to clients. 1.15.1 caps the client DATApply.log size. The log already appended across runs (every write is Add-Content), but had no size limit; it now rolls over to a single .lo_ companion once it reaches MaxLogSizeMB (default 5 MB) and starts a fresh .log, keeping on-disk size to about 2x the cap while preserving recent history (CMTrace shows the .log/.lo_ pair together). Re-sync to restage the updated apply script. 2.0.0 reworks the admin GUI from WinForms to a modern WPF interface and raises the module to PowerShell 7.4+ (CompatiblePSEditions Core). Start-DATGui now hosts the window on a dedicated STA runspace so it launches correctly under pwsh (which defaults to MTA). The five tabs (Models, SCCM Settings, Progress, Package Management, Deploy Applications) and every existing operation are preserved one-to-one - only the presentation layer changed. The client-side apply scripts stay Windows PowerShell 5.1 compatible and are unaffected. This is the foundation for the first-class Intune deployment support (Win32 apps and native driver-update profiles) landing in subsequent 2.x releases. 2.1.0 fixes the WPF GUI event handlers - Connect, Refresh Models, and the other buttons reported a null window/controls reference because the handler scriptblocks did not retain Initialize-DATMainWindow local variables under the STA-runspace host. The shared controls map, window, cursors, and log list box now live in module scope, which the handler scriptblocks can see. Also adds light/dark theming that follows the Windows app setting (Set-DATWindowTheme reads AppsUseLightTheme and swaps the window DynamicResource brushes) and a responsive Grid/DockPanel layout with proportional star-sizing so the window scales cleanly with its size. 2.1.1 actually fixes the GUI event handlers - 2.1.0 moved the shared state to module scope, but WPF dispatches events re-entrantly on the STA runspace and that context does not resolve PowerShell variable scope (neither locals nor $script:) - only module functions resolve. Every handler and timer tick is now a closure (GetNewClosure) that bakes in the controls map, window, and cursors; mutable cross-handler state lives in one shared hashtable captured by those closures; and ConfigMgr connection state is read through the Get-DATCMState module function. Theme detection now reads AppsUseLightTheme via the .NET registry API so dark mode is detected reliably in the child runspace. 2.1.2 fixes the follow-on failure 2.1.1 introduced - GetNewClosure rebinds each handler to a throwaway module that cannot see this module own functions, so the closured handlers failed with Get-DATComboText / Show-DATWindowMessage not recognized. Handlers are now plain scriptblocks (so module functions resolve) and fetch their state through a Get-DATGui module function, since a module-function call is the only thing the WPF re-entrant event context resolves reliably. Settings load and auto-connect run in the window Loaded handler with the same pattern, so saved settings are restored again, and the theme is re-applied in Loaded. 2.1.3 fixes button clicks (2.1.2 restored settings load via the Loaded event, but clicks still failed with the helper functions not recognized). The Loaded event fires while the module call is still on the stack, so module functions resolve there; button clicks fire later from the WPF message pump - a re-entrant native callback that resolves commands only from the runspace global session state, where module-private functions are invisible. Start-DATGui now dot-sources the module into the GUI runspace global scope in addition to importing it, so every DAT function is reachable from the re-entrant event handlers. 2.1.3 launched nothing at all (silent failure): the global-scope load used . on the .psm1 path, but PowerShell only dot-sources .ps1 files and tried to run the .psm1 as an external program, so the module never loaded globally and Show-DATMainWindow was undefined. 2.1.4 loads the module body globally by building a scriptblock from the .psm1 text (seeding PSScriptRoot) and dot-sourcing that, which correctly defines every function in the GUI runspace global scope. Start-DATGui also now surfaces any GUI-runspace startup error to the host and to a DATGui-startup.log, so a launch failure is never silent again. The GUI state accessors (Set-DATGui / Get-DATGui) use $global:DATGui so handlers always read the object the window was wired with.'
    PowerShellVersion = '7.4'
    CompatiblePSEditions = @('Core')
    FunctionsToExport = @(
        'Get-DATDriverPack'
        'Get-DATBIOSUpdate'
        'Invoke-DATSync'
        'Test-DATCatalogHealth'
        'Update-DATCatalogSources'
        'Start-DATGui'
        'Export-DATReport'
        'Register-DATQueueLogSubscriber'
        'Invoke-DATRemovePackages'
        'Invoke-DATCleanupOverlayPackages'
        'Invoke-DATDeployApplications'
        'Update-DATApplicationCommands'
        'Connect-DATIntune'
        'Disconnect-DATIntune'
        'Test-DATIntuneConnection'
        'Get-DATIntuneWin32App'
        'Find-DATIntuneEntraGroup'
    )
    CmdletsToExport   = @()
    VariablesToExport  = @()
    AliasesToExport    = @()
    PrivateData        = @{
        PSData = @{
            Tags       = @('SCCM', 'ConfigMgr', 'Intune', 'Graph', 'Drivers', 'BIOS', 'Dell', 'Lenovo', 'Microsoft', 'Surface', 'OSD', 'Automation')
            ProjectUri = 'https://github.com/kevinphillips/DriverAutomationRework'
            LicenseUri = 'https://github.com/kevinphillips/DriverAutomationRework/blob/main/LICENSE'
        }
    }
}
